["Issue 224701: Can't access google.com", 'Version: 26.0.1410.40 beta-m
OS: Windows 7

Bug: very frequently, on my home computer, I can't access google.com at all.  I've tried http: and https: and get the same result.  Reaching google.ca works.  All other sites works too.  I can reach google.com using IE.  I have to close my browser and restart it.  It's very annoying.

The error I get is:

This webpage is not available
The webpage at https://www.google.com/ might be temporarily down or it may have moved permanently to a new web address.
Error 15 (net::ERR_SOCKET_NOT_CONNECTED): Unknown error.


This may be related to the integrated Chrome / Google Search experiment, hence the "Restrict-View-Google" label.  I can't remember how to disable the experiment so I could not try that.', '']

['Issue 254188: content_shell is way too slow in debug builds', "Testing on my mac as of r208535/r153027, for example ...

in release mode, fast/html takes 4.5s in a single worker, and 116s in debug (~20x slower). 

jquery/ takes 11s in release, 404s in debug (~40x slower).

The cycle times on the bots are similarly much slower ...

http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.webkit/stats/WebKit%20Mac10.7
http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.webkit/stats/WebKit%20Mac10.7%20(dbg)

average cycle time of 18 minutes in release vs. 130+ min in debug, webkit_tests 800s vs. 8000s (10x) (6 workers on each bot).

linux is not much better (~ 650s vs. 4500s, 6 workers each):

http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.webkit/stats/WebKit%20Linux  
http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.webkit/stats/WebKit%20Linux%20(dbg)

To get a very rough data point, I did some testing of fast/html and jquery on my mac using a release-mode libv8.dylib instead of a debug build, and got substantial speedups (10s and 83s respectively, for 2x slower and 8x slower, though I think  there's a couple of seconds of overhead in run-webkit-tests, making the numbers closer to 5x instead of 2x).

So, v8's part of the problem but not the whole problem. 

For comparision, if you look at net_unittests on Mac10.7 (random sample of one data point) we have 67 secs vs. 610 secs:

http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.mac/builders/Mac10.7%20Tests%20%283%29/builds/16128
http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.mac/builders/Mac%2010.7%20Tests%20%28dbg%29%282%29/builds/13864

and content_browsertests takes 153s vs. 260s):

http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.mac/builders/Mac10.7%20Tests%20%281%29/builds/13674

Obviously, there's a lot of variance here, from 2x slower to 10x slower in other targets, but 30x slower is too much IMO.

As one last data point, the run-webkit-tests timeouts for debug are only 2x slower than release. We should probably at least adjust these to what we expect a real multiple should be.", '']

['Issue 310815: Optional host permissions forgotten after browser restart', 'Version: 31.0.1650.26
OS: ChromeOS, Linux

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Install an extension with "optional_permissions": [ "<all_urls>" ],
2. Use chrome.permissions.request to request permission to a specific host (e.g. "http://www.google.com")
3. Use chrome.permissions.contains to verify that we have permissions to "http://www.google.com".
4. Restart the browser (or sign out/restart chromeos)
5. Use chrome.permissions.contains again to verify that we have permissions to "http://www.google.com".

What is the expected output? What do you see instead?
The expected result is (I think) that a granted optional permission persists across restarts, for as long as the extension is installed. The actual result is that, after the restart, chrome.permissions.contains returns false, and the extension needs to request permission again after every restart.

(For an example, use the chrome remote desktop app with a host that has third-party authentication enabled [you can follow up offline for instructions on how to set that up])', '']

['Issue 274860: Use run_benchmark instead of run_measurement on the bots', "run_benchmark is ready to use!
tools/perf/run_benchmark list to list the available tests, and tools/perf/run_benchmark <benchmark_name> to run a test.

We'd like to use exclusively run_benchmark on the bots, so that we can add and remove tests, configs, and expectations using only Chromium source changes and no bot restarts.

Telemetry GPU tests have an equivalent script, content/test/gpu/run_gpu_test. We should run both of them.", '']

['Issue 244628: Chrome ignored StartSession failure from the session manager.', 'On ChromeOS, when the NSS database is corrupted (which I did intentionally here, but it has happened in the field too), the session manager tries to open it to verify that the owner key is in there, and fails.

It then returns failure from StartSession, which should cause the login session to fail, but it doesn't.

Attached is an entire log for a "successful" login with the nssdb file ~chronos/user/.pki/nssdb/key4.db corrupted by copying over it with zeros from /dev/zero.', '']

['Issue 212716: Remote try-bot HW Test Step requirements', 'This is a bug to collect the different requirements we have to start running the HWTest step for remote try-bots. 

Information we need:

rcui/sosa
* How large the try-bot pool is. (This will tell us what we need to support try-bots)
* Do we need the same turnaround time from the HWTest step as the commit queue for remote try-bot runs? (This tells us how many dedicated machines we need). 
* How long it takes on average to run through a try-bot run. 


nsylvain:
From the chrome-infra side we need to understand how we can modify the network to accomodate try-bots running in a different vlan than the autotest proxy. We currently have an autotest proxy running on master2.m2. It is my understanding that we will not be able to communicate from M4 to M2 vlans. We will either need to poke a hole between the two vlans or set up another proxy. Ideally we would poke a hole. 


Any other hurdles that were missed here?', '']

['Issue 517495: Misceallanous Coverity Scan issues', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.3; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/44.0.2403.130 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
Besides the other issue I already reported, and the ones that I submitted patches for, Coverity Scan also complained about a few other things. These are things I either don't have time to investigate, or where I think you guys can clarify things much faster than I can, since you are more familiar with the code.

Note that I only ran Coverity Scan over *ring*, not all of BoringSSL. Also note that Coverity tries to restrict people from using its tools to analyze other peoples' code, but I have some evidence that indicates that that is easy to subvert. So, if any of these are actually legit problems people will be able to find them very easily through Coverity Scan.

Regarding this shift issue: I believe there is a bug in Coverity's understanding of the shift operator.

What is the expected behavior?
Coverity stops telling scary stories about the code.

What went wrong?
Some scary stories are being told, particularly regarding out-of-bounds array writes in the DES code and a potential memory barrier issue in urandom.c.

Did this work before? N/A 

Chrome version: 44.0.2403.130  Channel: stable
OS Version: 6.3
Flash Version: 

Sorry this isn't a good bug report. Since I'm not going to be fixing these issues, I thought I should at least relay them to you rather than just filing them away.", '']

['Issue 143984: Proxy resolving keeps getting retried when PAC script throws an error', 'Chrome Version       : 21.0.1180.82
OS Version: OS X 10.7.4
UserAgentString: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_7_4) AppleWebKit/537.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/21.0.1180.82 Safari/537.1

and

Chrome Version       : 22.0.1229.8 dev
OS Version: OS X 10.6.8
UserAgentString: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/537.4 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/22.0.1229.8 Safari/537.4

Other browsers tested:
Firefox 15.0 beta (on OS X 10.6.8 machine)
Safari 5.1.7 (6534.57.2; on OS X 10.6.8 machine)


What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Enable "Auto Proxy Discovery" in (system) settings for current connection.
2. Assume network serves an invalid WPAD/PAC file (see [a][b] and "additional information" section).

[a]: Located the WPAD/PAC file via trying "wpad.(DNS root)/wpad.dat" as per https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Proxy_Autodiscovery_Protocol
[b]: PAC file for the network I encountered this issue on: https://d2p12wh0p3fo1n.cloudfront.net/files/20120821/wpad.dat


What is the expected result?
Browser acts normally / does not consume high CPU.


What happens instead?
Chrome steadily consumes up to 250% CPU (on a 4 core system).



Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot if possible.

chrome://net-internals shows a sustained tens of thousands network events per second.[c] (On both machines, this causes net-internals to hang either immediately or after a couple seconds. Tab crashes after a few more seconds.)

Looks like Chrome is discovering the WPAD/PAC file properly, but because the file causes a JavaScript error, Chrome does not fail elegantly and re-tries the fetch/parse ad nauseum.[c][d]

While this is happening, Chrome is usable and can properly access the internet (likely proxy-less), but the "Browser" process continues to consume CPU.

Looks like Chrome networking code should delay retries and/or use a maximum number of retries for the given auto-discovered PAC hostname/filename. (Chrome does seem to properly fall-back to a non-proxy state while this is going on, which would be the expected behavior for nonexistant PAC files.)

[c] Screenshot displaying net-internals event log: https://d2p12wh0p3fo1n.cloudfront.net/files/20120821/001.png
[d] Screenshot displaying PAC_JAVASCRIPT_ERROR detail: https://d2p12wh0p3fo1n.cloudfront.net/files/20120821/002.png
(notes: 10.100.1.100 is the network's primary DNS server.)', '']

['Issue 215160: Investigate Re-Enabling crashcollect to gather useful information when a machine returns from the dead', "Chrome Version     :  N/A
OS Version         :  2657.0.0
Type of computer   :  all
Network info       :  all

What new or enhanced feature are you proposing?
When cleanup jobs run, they create an empty 'sysinfo' directory
in the logs, but don't populate it.  For debugging certain
problems, it would be helpful to gather the standard sysinfo
content (notably, the content of /var/logs) during the cleanup job.

What goal would this enhancement help you achieve?
In some recent bugs, a system has failed by going offline for
an extended period of time, and then spontaneously coming
back online.  For those failures, we'd like the contents of
/var/log/messages for the time period that the unit was offline.
Recent examples of this symptom are in bug 32181 and bug 31748.

In some cases, the logs from subsequent jobs on the same host can
collect enough of /var/log to be useful, but sometimes the next
job re-images the host, clobbering /var/log.  Consistently attempting
to gather logs from the target during cleanup should improve our
odds of getting useful data.", '']

['Issue 243601: content_shell speed regressions compared to DumpRenderTree cause tryserver backlogs', "We've switched over from DumpRenderTree to content_shell for running layout  tests, which is cool because we are now running code paths much closer to what chrome does.

However, it appears that content_shell is significantly slower at the moment on Mac, Linux, and Windows. On Linux, at least running locally (z600 + SSD), It looks about 35% slower. On Windows, we're closer to 100% (2x) slower (z620 + ssd), and Mac, 125% (2.5x) slower (all of these are release builds).

We seem to see similar slowdowns on the chromium.webkit waterfalls as well. I haven't mined the numbers on the try servers yet, but the tryservers seemed to have 20-30+ jobs backed up all afternoon and evening on Win and Mac.

It is not yet clear to me how much of this slowdown is intrinsic to the cutover, and how much might just be that we haven't spent a lot of time tuning content_shell yet.

However, we either need to come up with a couple of easy fixes, or add a bunch more win and linux VMs. 

interestingly, I'm not seeing the same backups on the mac; I'm guessing we had lots of mac capacity already and were able to absorb this.

dev folks -- can you comment on whether you expected content_shell to be this much slower, or if you think these are likely bugs that are fairly easy to fix?

infra folks - can and should we spin up a bunch of vms in the mean time?", '']

['Issue 155612: .tmp files being left in download folder after downloads are completed', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.11 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/23.0.1271.26 Safari/537.11

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Download file from any website/source
2. Check download folder
3. 

What is the expected behavior?

What went wrong?
Chrome is not cleaning up .tmp files after completing downloads.

Example URL:

Did this work before? Yes All prior versions

Chrome version: 23.0.1271.26  Channel: beta
OS Version: 6.1 (Windows 7, Windows Server 2008 R2)', '']

['Issue 431695: With impl-side painting ScheduledActionAnimate incorrectly skips animation during initial activation', "To allow animation updates to occur within a single frame (IE before DRAW), if something updates the animation state we want to run the ANIMATE step again.

Without impl-side painting, the animations state is updated in the commit stage. This is correctly handled in all cases.

With impl-side painting, the animation state is first copied to the pending-tree and then actually updated in the activate stage, thus if the scheduler then calls ANIMATE between the COMMIT and ACTIVATE, the updates **don't** get applied!

This issue was discovered in the interactive_ui_tests on ChromeOS Debug build when 
https://codereview.chromium.org/595973002 landed. This appears to be because of the usage of a Browser Compositor.

The bug exhibited through the current steps;

  1) LayerAnimationController::Animate was called in the COMMIT state. The controller didn't update its time because while animations existed, no observers were attached and LayerAnimationController::HasValueObservers() returned false.

  2) The activate step attached a bunch of observers to the animations, meaning that LayerAnimationController::HasValueObservers() returns true.

  3) The draw step called LayerAnimationController::UpdateState, which failed a DCHECK inside LayerAnimationController::UpdateState. The DCHECK checks that an animation time has been provided which essentially verifies that the controller's Animate has been called before updating state.

As ACTIVATE appears before ANIMATE in SchedulerStateMachine::NextAction() this only occurs SchedulerStateMachine::ShouldActivatePendingTree returns false for a period after a commit, during which Scheduler::ProcessScheduledActions() is called.

I believe this bug has existed from when the ANIMATE step was introduced. Thus has existed for the last 6 months and since subversion revision 267338 meaning it exists in the current stable version.", '']

['Issue 481034: Move libvpx out of DEPS', "libvpx currently lives in src/third_party/libvpx and is versioned in chromium via DEPS. We would prefer to have it directly in the chromium tree.

Benefits:
 - run trybots on changes before they are merged
 - don't need to explain roll procedure to infrequent committers

Cons:
 - may need to check out the whole chromium tree to make changes
   (currently i check out just the deps repo, and have a separate checkout with just src/ to update the DEPS file)

I've already run this past WebRTC which is a downstream consumer of libvpx. They roll chromium revisions as a whole, not specific libvpx revisions, so they will be unaffected.", '']

['Issue 197236: Speed up the switching process (wiping) from factory test image to release image', 'Currently running a postinst (if both partition A and B exist) takes 24 seconds. That's too long for most factory process (and auto updating).

If we take a close look, the monster is chromeos-setimage, which spends most of its time running verity, to update grub and syslinux (the legacy boot loaders on x86).

In other words, we spend lots of time
 - updating records for legacy devices, even on H2C ChromeOS devices that never uses them
 - computing redundant info, even if the hash was already calculated before (ex, from dump_kernel_config in kernel partition).

I think we can improve this by only re-calculating rootfs hash if a "--rehash" param is assigned, otherwise it should simply pull the hash from kernel partition (if available).

The action item may include:
 - add "--rehash" option to chromeos-setimage
 - dump_kernel_config and update hash according to kernel partition, if not rehashing.
 - search code base to correct all scripts calling chromeos-setimage, if they need rehashing legacy partitions.', '']

['Issue 213532: Update the Autotest installer code to avoid reinstalling the same version.', 'We are installing a lot of machines and the more suites we run the higher probability we have in reinstalling a machine to the exact same image.\n\nWe should investigate whether or not our install code can reliably confirm that a system is in fact on the image we want to install on the DUT. If it is skip the install process but ensure the proper labels are on the machine already or are added.', '']

['Issue 138175: navigation gesture should bias for more horizontal motion', 'On MacOS, sideways dragging of the touchpad first shows an affordance and then navigates once the sideways drag exceeds some threshold.

I regularly go back / forwards with this gesture by accident which prompts me to think that we should adjust it in some way.

I propose that we could try the following:
*  require that the horizontal scroll to initiate be in a thinner band
*  consider adding some kind of scrolling-on-rails event
*  tune the threshold to initiate the gesture

Thoughts?', '']

['Issue 481545: Open new tab immediately after currently active tab', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_3) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/44.0.2383.0 Safari/537.36

What is the expected behavior?

['Issue 487028: text-rendering: optimizeLegibility breaks Range client rect API', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_10_3) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/42.0.2311.135 Safari/537.36

Example URL:
http://jsfiddle.net/nicksantos/u7cghkjz/

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Create an element with text-rendering: optimizeLegibility
2. Create a range at the last cursor position in that element
3. Ask for the range's getClientRect

The code in the attached JSFiddle demonstrates the problem more succinctly:
http://jsfiddle.net/nicksantos/u7cghkjz/

What is the expected behavior?
The client rect is at the rightmost side of the element

What went wrong?
The client rect is at the leftmost side of the element

Does it occur on multiple sites: Yes

Is it a problem with a plugin? No 

Did this work before? N/A 

Does this work in other browsers? Yes 

Chrome version: 42.0.2311.135  Channel: stable
OS Version: OS X 10.10.3
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 17.0 r0

The issue is not reproducible on Safari8 or Firefox", '']

['Issue 146521: Chrome + JQuery weird behavior when reloading a page', "Chrome Version       : 21.0.1180.89
OS Version: Ubuntu 12.04
URLs (if applicable) :
Other browsers tested:
  Add OK or FAIL after other browsers where you have tested this issue:
     Safari 5: OK
  Firefox 4.x: OK
     IE 7/8/9: OK

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Create a page using JQuery dialog + DOM manipulation
2. Reload the page twice or more

What is the expected result?
The page reloads, is displayed and javascript code is execupted


What happens instead?
If the developer tools panel is opened, Chrome won't display the page at all. Instead, the console display an error message as follow (nnn if the last line of the HTML document):

(x) GET http://www.domain.tld/pagename                  pagename:nnn

If the developer tools panel is closed, Chrome displays the page, but won't execute any script. Opening the developper tools panel afterwards, the console displays

(x) Failed to load resource                http://www.domain.tld/pagename

Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot if
possible.

I'm facing a very strange and specific issue with Chrome (21.0.1180.89). I have a page which makes use of JQuery and its dialog() feature. First, the page loads fine, the JQuery dialog is shown on the screen has expected and everything works fine: other JQuery interactions (clicks, ajax, etc.) also works perfectly. Then, without interacting with the page, if I simply reload it, Chrome starts to do weird things:

If the developer tools panel is opened, Chrome won't display the page at all. Instead, the console display an error message as follow (nnn if the last line of the HTML document):
(x) GET http://www.domain.tld/pagename                   pagename:nnn 

If the developer tools panel is closed, Chrome displays the page, but won't execute any script. Opening the developper tools panel afterwards, the console displays
(x) Failed to load resource             http://www.domain.tld/pagename
Clicking the link takes me to the first line of the HTML document.

More over, if I close the developer tools panel and hit reload a first time, the document keeps being loaded but the screen remains blank. If I hit reload once again, the document keeps being loaded AND, this time, the HTML code is rendered. But no script is ran.

Here comes the best! Now, if I modify my source HTML file simply adding or removing a white-space and then reload the page, everything works fine. If I reload it once again just after, Chrome restarts to do the weird things described above. The same thing applies if I restart Chrome: first display works perfectly, next ones fail.

I thought about an extension related issue. Trying in incognito mode without any extension and deactivating all plugins, the problem remains exactly the same: same behavior, same messages in console.

UserAgentString: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/537.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/21.0.1180.89 Safari/537.1", '']

['Issue 69723: Passwords are shared with user data dir differents', 'Chrome Version       : 10.0.634.0 dev
URLs (if applicable) : any that saves a password
Other browsers tested: NA

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. create one shortcut for Chrome with default user-data-dir
2. create another shortcut for Chrome with other user-data-dir
3. start Google Chrome with "default" user-data-dir 
4. access a url that saves password in default 
5. closes default instance
6. start Google Chrome with "another" user-data-dir
7. check that password are there 


What is the expected result?
I expect that passwords are isolated in each user data dir

What happens instead?
Passwords are shared, so, when I delete in one profile, it was deleted in another profile

I'm not sure if this issue is a security one, if it is a simple bug, or an implementation decision, so I'm submitting it.', '']

['Issue 360118: Create BrowserTest for Guest Sessions', 'There are numerous little differences between browsers using a regular profile and those using a guest profile.  There should be a browser-test for Guest sessions.

It should verify that...

- verify profile is "incognito"
- extensions are not present and cannot be installed
- bookmarks cannot be added and the bookmark bar cannot be displayed
- sign-in not available (may be an "incognito" thing)
- settings are unavailable (or very reduced)

Please comment with further suggestions.', '']

["Issue 254262: Fixed 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\attrib.exe' string in cygtar.py", 'Describe infrastructure request/issue:

I downloaded the r197479 version and when I trying to execute "gclient runhooks --force" I got many errors which shows "C:\Windows\System32\attrib.exe" is not a vaild Win32 application, and I ignored all the errors when trying to build the source code in VS2010, it also gives me the same error.

I found "attrib.exe" is in file "project\src\native_client\build\cygtar.py" at line 92:

      return subprocess.call(['cmd', '/C', 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\attrib.exe',
                              '+S', ToNativePath(filepath)])

Which is using a fixed string.

My system was installed at driver letter P (P:\Windows), and the driver letter C is another system which not currently using, so the code makes this problem.

If this is a new buildbot slave:

OS: Windows7
Version: 7601
Bitness: 64
Waterfall:', '']

["Issue 491303: parallel_emerge doesn't work as expected with --sysroot=/build/amd64-host", "It seems to be installing packages into the host ('/') instead of the said sysroot. This is different from how emerge-amd64-host behaves, which is correct. According to bsimonnet@ this is likely because of how we setup make.conf for host boards, which uses chromeos/config/make.conf.amd64-host (and not make.conf.amd64-target, like normal boards). Specifically, the ROOT env variable in parallel_emerge runs is set to / instead of /build/amd64-host.\n\nThe workaround is to also use --root=/build/amd64-host when running parallel_emerge. This produces the expected result.", '']

Just add --embeddable command line parameter', 'Add the possibility to launch Chrome in a hidden, chromeless fullscreen window, but without any WM_GETMINMAXINFO restrictions and report back to STDOUT a HWND id; launcher applications should have the possibility to grab this handle and convert the window into a child, via SetParent();

Or

chrome.exe --embed-into=0x0225189
Should cause it to be launched as a WM_CHILD and use the passed handle as its parent.

See http://stackoverflow.com/a/10992208/608886', '']

['Issue 100367: Extension content scripts see the value of window.opener', "Chrome Version       : 16.0.904.0
URLs (if applicable) : popups
Other browsers tested: -

Extensions are not able to see the value of window.opener
Due to this, extensions are not able to figure out what URL opened their popup, so they could for example close the popup when it matches an 'advertisement popup'.

Preventing a popup from opening at all isn't possible, so the only way to do this, is to request window.opener.location.href and close it as fast as possible if matched.", '']

['Issue 421220: NaCl SDK: UDP Send lockup', 'After time, when sending UDP packets, the socket gets in a state where it can no longer send.

1)      At some point, a udp packet is sent, and when the UdpSendWork::Run callback method is called, it returns with an error -11 (PP_ERROR_INPROGRESS).

2)      That causes the SocketNode::SetError_Locked method to be called, setting some error status and also setting the local variable last_errno_ to the error value.  However, it doesn’t seem to set any other state that would indicate to the Berkeley socket implementation that there was an error (other than could be queried by getsockopt()).

3)      The next sendto() on this socket eventually calls SocketNode::SendHelper()

4)      SocketNode::SendHelper calls wait.WaitOnEvent(POLLOUT,ms) where ms = -1 (the default).  This function never returns, apparently because of the state set earlier in the call to SetError_Locked and because the condition variable managed in EventListenerLock::WaitOnEvent is never set.', '']

['Issue 93555: Chromoting: Windows Firewall Causes Crash', "client: OS X, Chrome 15.0.856.0, webapp from tot 1.1.20036.2923
Host: Win7, Chrome 15.0.856.0, webapp from tot 1.1.20036.2923

What steps will reproduce the problem?

5. After a few more seconds, the host browser will display a message saying that the plug-in has crashed.

['Issue 415490: [WebRTC] Video takes long time in being rendering when first RTP packets are lost', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_4) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/37.0.2062.120 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Chrome-A establishes an audio+video session with a WebRTC server.
2. Once ICE and DTLS is done Chrome-A starts sending its RTP.
3. The server does nothing with the RTP (ignores it).
4. Chrome-B also joins and connects to the server.
5. The server routes RTP form Chrome-A to Chrome-B and vice-versa.

What is the expected behavior?
Media from Chrome-A should be immediately rendered when Chrome-B establishes the WebRTC session/connection with the server.

What went wrong?
It takes long time (in version 37 current stable it may be ~30 seconds, in Canary 39.0.2161.3 it takes ~5 seconds) until the audio and video is rendered in the HTML <video> element (which has play="true" and all the common stuff).

Did this work before? N/A 

Chrome version: 39.0.2161.3 canary (64-bit)  Channel: canary
OS Version: OS X 10.9.4
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 15.0 r0

When Chrome-B joins the "conference" and starts sending its media to the server (and the server routes it to Chrome-A), Chrome-A automatically renders the audio+video form Chrome-A.

It also happens if a single Chrome tab establishes a WebRTC session with itself by sending the media through a TURN or media server that, artificially, ignores the RTP packets for a while. This is, once the server allows the incoming RTP to be sent back to Chrome,  the "remoteVideo" <video> element does not render the audio+video immediately but it takes more than 10 seconds to it.

The SDP generated by the server (in the case above) is ok and indicates the correct SSRC that the server sets to the RTP packets before forwarding them to Chrome-B. Same happens if the SSRC is not overridden by the server.

This issue does not happen in Firefox in which the receiver always starts rendering the incoming RTP audio/video in the corresponding <video> element with no delay at all. It happens just in Chrome and just when the first RTP packets of the incoming stream have been lost or not sent to the receiver for any reason (for example, because the receiver joined the "conference" later when other were already exchanging RTP).', '']

['Issue 58495: ChromeOS initial cwnd tuning', 'We should set the initial cwnd to 10 as per http://static.googleusercontent.com/external_content/untrusted_dlcp/research.google.com/en/us/pubs/archive/36640.pdf

To do so, the ip route command can be used:
     /sbin/ip route change default via $ipaddress dev $ethdev initcwnd 10


We should also turn off slow-start-after-idle, or make idle be much longer.  To turn it off, you can use this:
     /sbin/sysctl -w net.ipv4.tcp_slow_start_after_idle=0', '']

['Issue 163375: Focus issues with XQuartz', "Version: 25.0.1323.1 dev
OS: Mac OS X 10.8.2

Chromoting pref pane shows 24.0.1312
Chrome Remote Desktop is 1.9.1271.42

XQuartz is at 2.7.4, but I suspect it happens for nearly any version.

1. Enable Chromoting into a Mac.
2. Launch XQuartz, start up a couple of XTerms
3. Click around the windows.

Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 19.0 r0

['Issue 473417: Very slow input performance within a simple table that contains a checkbox', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.101 Safari/537.36

['Issue 395464: Problems since GPU upgrade', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.3; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/37.0.2062.20 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Open multiple pages
2. Let all of them load
3. Switch to a different tab

What is the expected behavior?
Page is displayed properly

What went wrong?
Pages load real slow, sometimes need to manually switch to them to begin actual loading (until then, the pale circle goes around slow). After switching tabs, the displayed page is completely white, frozen, sometimes crashes, sometimes Shockwave Flash crashes.

This is especially annoying when there are multiple tabs needed, and switching between them takes minutes.

Crashed report ID: 

How much crashed? Just one tab

Is it a problem with a plugin? No 

Did this work before? Yes Before hardware upgrade

Chrome version: 37.0.2062.20  Channel: beta
OS Version: 6.3
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 14.0 r0

The problem started when I switched some parts in my laptop - mainly, the CPU and GPU. My laptop is an HP EliteBook 8530w - originally came with an Intel P8400 and AMD ATI HD 3650M, which I upgraded to an Intel T9700 and Nvidia Quadro FX 770M.

The problem was slighly reduced when I updated the drivers to the latest Beta, but still not perfect, and Flash crashes no matter what (especially if it's not the current tab).", '']

["Issue 302450: Add support for Unicode 6.3's directional isolate formatting characters", 'Unicode 6.3, released today, contains major changes in the Unicode Bidirectional Algorithm, and https://code.google.com/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=242238 has been filed to track the work to support these changes in Blink.

The following is more information on one of the two major new features, support for directional isolates. It consists of the following pieces:

- Added directional isolate formatting characters (http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#Explicit_Directional_Isolates and http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#Terminating_Explicit_Directional_Isolates)

- Added values to the Bidi_Class property for each of the new formatting characters: LRI, RLI, FSI, and PDI.

- Modified rule http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#P2 to skip over directional isolates when determining the default paragraph direction.

- Extensively revised http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#Explicit_Levels_and_Directions and its existing X rules to formalize the algorithm for matching a PDF with the embedding or override initiator whose scope it terminates, and integrate it with the new formatting characters.

- Added rules http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#X5a, http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#X5b, http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#X5c and http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#X6a to describe the effect of the new formatting characters on explicit embedding levels.

- Modified rule http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#X10 to make the isolating run sequence the unit to which subsequent rules are applied (instead of the level run).

- Modified rule http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#W1 to change an NSM preceded by an isolate initiator or PDI into ON.

- Modified rules http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#N1 and http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#N2 to treat the new isolate formatting characters the same as neutral characters (bidi class ON); see http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#NI).

- Modified rule http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#L1 to treat the new isolate formatting characters the same as whitespace (bidi class WS).

Revision 28 of the document cited above (http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/tr9-28.html) shows all the changes in the specification marked in yellow.

The new version of the test data (http://www.unicode.org/Public/UNIDATA/BidiTest.txt) includes many cases that test various aspects of isolates. The ones between "FSI ON EN EN PDI; 3" and "ON RLI ON FSI ON R LRI ON PDI ON PDI ON PDI ON; 4" are especially relevant.

For some simple examples of isolate usage, see http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#L2 and http://www.unicode.org/reports/tr9/#Formatting.

For the rationale behind directional isolates, see http://goo.gl/K6qtV.', '']

['Issue 377059: Allowing full preroll buffer discard and playback from time 0 needs append window filtering to occur prior to timestamp>0 checks in CFP algorithm', "To allow more than 1 full frame discard will require the check for frame start time >= presentation start time to occur *after* append window filtering.

This bug tracks the ToT Chromium implementation of this swap, in anticipation of gapless AAC landing (https://codereview.chromium.org/276573002/).

The gist is, if playback is meant to start from time 0, yet begin with the result of decode halfway through a second frame fed to the decoder, then we would need to:
1) set timestampOffset(negative ~1.5 frame durations)
2) set appendWindowStart(0)
3) append (eventual full preroll frame)-> it gets PTS=-1.5 initially, decode err currently per spec. By doing append window filtering first, though, it would be held aside as a pending preroll buffer and dropped by frame processor otherwise
4) append (frame with rest of preroll + expected data to start at time 0)-> this frame gets a preroll added to it, timestamp offset + partial start append window clipping should adjust the frame's PTS and DTS to time 0.
5) profit :)", '']

['Issue 254973: Feature request: devtools to debug EventSource', "Chrome Version : 27.0.1453.116 OS Version: OS X 10.7.5 WebSockets are starting to get easier to debug in devtools, but having each frame of EventSource requests would be really useful for debugging. I'd expect to be able to see the raw lines of content that are sent down the connection, but also the events they emit. For instance, we were testing an EventSource connection and sending an HTML snippet upstream: data: data:

Indented

But we found it was stripping one space instead of it being indented twice. It turned out the parser was expecting a space after the colon, but if we had a tool to see the raw string and the object and event being triggered, it would have been much faster to diagnose. Thanks!", '']

@zelidrag to triage.', '']

['Issue 221875: Text box keybindings like OS X, Gnome, Emacs', 'Chromium 27.0.1421.1 (Developer Build 184310) 
Platform 3757.0.2013_02_25_1614 (Developer Build - hexxeh) vanilla x86-generic
Type of computer   :  Macbook Air

There doesn't seem to be an option in Chrome OS to have what I would call "normal" keybindings in text areas: ctrl-a for beginning of line, ctrl-e for end of line, ctrl-b for backward, etc.

Chrome on OS X behaves "correctly", like other OS X apps.  Chrome on Linux follows Gnome's configuration.  I haven't tried Windows or KDE environments.

I'm sure you're trying to keep configuration to a minimum, but I think this will be important to a lot of users coming from OS X or Linux.

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Boot into Chrome OS.
2. Type some stuff in a text box, such as the omnibox, or compose an email.
3. Type Ctrl-a.

What is the expected output?

The cursor goes to the start of the line.

What do you see instead?

The entire text area is selected.  (Perhaps this is the norm in Windows and would be preferred by some users?)

How frequently does this problem reproduce? (Always, sometimes, hard to
reproduce?)

Always.

What is the impact to the user, and is there a workaround? If so, what is
it?

No known workaround.', '']

["Issue 32591: Restore tabs on startup doesn't work when close an incognito window after the main window", 'Chrome Version       : 4.0.295.0

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Open several tabs in your primary Chrome session
2. Enable "reopen the pages that were open last" under startup options
3. Close Chrome
4. Reopen Chrome; previous tabs are reopened
5. Open an incognito window
6. Close primary chrome window
7. Close incognito window
8. Launch Chrome

What is the expected result?
Chrome should open with the tabs present in the non-incognito window.

What happens instead?
Chrome opens with a single home page tab.

Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot if
possible.

It's clear that Chrome restores the state of the last window closed in all 
cases.  This makes sense with standard windows, but is illogical behavior 
when the last window open is incognito.  Incognito sessions are by their 
very nature stateless, and therefore will never result in a saved session.  
The user may inadvertently lose their session state by leaving an incognito 
window open in the background.  Instead, Chrome should save the tabs in the 
last open stateful (normal) window in all cases, and disregard incognito 
windows entirely in terms of this feature.', '']

['Issue 448546: Autofill detects section split incorrectly on POST donation page.', 'Version: 41.0.2269.0 (Official Build) canary

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Navigate to https://app.etapestry.com/onlineforms/PeninsulaOpenSpaceTrust/GiveToPOST.html
2. Autofill the form.

What is the expected output?
  The name in the "Tribute Gift (Optional)" section should not be autofilled -- this should be detected as a separate section.

What do you see instead?
  It is autofilled, verily.

The issue seems to be that the form asks for first/middle/last names in one section, and a full name in a different section; since Autofill treats these as different types, we don't detect a section break.', '']

['Issue 386201: Framebuffer erroneously cleared to opaque', 'Chrome Version       : Android WebView r276123
OS Version           : Android KitKat 4.4.2_r2

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1.  Create an application with 2 overlapping WebViews, with the top WebView having a transparent background.

What is the expected result?
You will be able to see the bottom WebView through the transparent portion of the top WebView.

What happens instead?
The transparent portion of the top WebView is opaque and is obscuring the bottom WebView.

Did this work before?
Yes, with the v30 version of Chromium WebView that ships with KitKat 4.4.2_r2.

What went wrong?
In latest code, there is a optimization the enables discarding of framebuffers.  
https://chromiumcodereview.appspot.com/23601013
This causes the GPU command buffer code to set the backbuffer_needs_clear_bits_ flag which clears the framebuffer in GLES2DecoderImpl::CheckFramebufferValid() using an alpha channel obtained from offscreen_target_color_format_ which is uninitialized as this is not an offscreen target and ends up clearing the buffer with an opaque alpha channel.  I think the proper fix is to clear with the back_buffer_color_format_', '']

['Issue 311594: Old .isolated.state can break compilation', 'What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Checkout Chrome
2. ninja -C out/Debug base_unittests_run
3. Edit the out/Debug/base_unittests.isolated.state file and change the path to the base_unittests.isolate file (i.e. make it an invalid path, emulating a developer working with some refactoring).
4. Remove the out/Debug/base_unittests.isolated file, so a new build will trigger the rule for .isolate files again.
5. ninja -C out/Debug base_unittests_run

Compilation will now fail.

What is the expected output? What do you see instead?
I expect that the old .isolated.state file will not cause compilation breakage. 
It now causes a build failure that can only be remedied with a clobber or by manually removing the leftover base_unittests.isolated.state file in the build output directory.

I assume this is a bug that should be fixed?

Please use labels and text to provide additional information.', '']

['Issue 288758: Add client side Speed Index implementation', "The Speed Index is a metric that better represents the user experience for loading a page and can be calculated from the paint rects that are exposed through dev tools: https://sites.google.com/a/webpagetest.org/docs/using-webpagetest/metrics/speed-index (it roughly boils down to the average time when content is rendered to the screen).

It has been very helpful for a lot of our optimization efforts but has only been available in a lab environment.  We should add an UMA histogram to report it from the field so we can have the same data available for real user browsing.

There are a lot of sources for paint information within Chrome and the best data will be from the compositor but in the short term we can use the paint rects from blink which will give us consistent data with what we capture in a lab.

The speed index calculation requires an end point.  For consistency we should use the end of the onload event which will give us visual metrics that align with out page load metrics but won't be terribly useful for single-page-apps (docs, mail, etc).", '']

['Issue 440069: Add light sensor for adjusting color theme for reader mode', 'OS: Android

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Go to a dark place
2. Enable reader mode.
3. Go to a website where reader mode is available.
4. Trigger reader mode.. 

What is the expected output?
A pleasant and readable reading experience.

What do you see instead?
A bright background and dark text. One has to open appearance setting to get a pleasant view.

Suggested solution:
Add a light sensor that will automatically adjust the color theme.
Android provides a lot of sensors, including light sensors, see http://developer.android.com/guide/topics/sensors/sensors_overview.html .

We can get callbacks whenever accuracy changes (high, medium, low, unreliable, no contact) and a separate callback for the light itself in lux. Android also provides helpful lux values for typical lighting environments: no moon, full moon, cloudy, sunrise, overcast, shade, sunlight and maximum sunlight.

There is also a knob we need to turn as in how often we callbacks. Shorter interval means more battery usage. They propose around 60 ms intervals for UI-related things, which is the category I believe this usage falls under.

One registers a listener in onResume and removes it in onPause, and based on the callbacks, we should call DistilledPagePrefs with the new theme.

The plan is to not use sepia for now, and only provide the light and dark themes automatically.
If we later choose to add user settings, we could provide: Automatic (default), Light, Sepia and Dark.

With only light and dark color schemes, the config basically ends up being: a threshold lux value for when to switch between the themes, plus the callback interval.', '']

['Issue 39355: alert() windows appear *under* extension popup; can appear to lock up X server', 'Chrome Version (from the about:version page): 5.0.342.7 (Official Build 42476) beta Is this the most recent version: presumably OS + version: (Google corp workstation) CPU architecture (32-bit / 64-bit): 64-bit Window manager: default URLs (if relevant): N/A Behavior in Linux Firefox: N/A Behavior in Windows Chrome (if you have access to it): Dunno What steps will reproduce the problem? 1. Create an extension with a browser or page action popup containing the following content:
click me
2. Run the extension, open the popup, and click on "click me". 3. If your X server appears to stop accepting input, press space bar to get it back. What is the expected result? - A visible alert window should appear and the user should be able to click it to close it. - The user should be able to interact with other (non-chrome) windows without first closing the alert window. What happens instead? - *Sometimes* the alert window appears directly under the popup where it cannot be seen. (Sometimes it appears elsewhere; I'm not sure what determines this.) - Because the extension's popup is active, Chrome grabs all input away from other X windows, presumably so that it can close the popup when the user clicks elsewhere. - But within Chrome, the alert() window is stealing all input, so the popup does not close when the user clicks. The combination of these three problems can lead the user to believe that their X server has stopped accepting input. They are unlikely to realize that an alert window is displayed, and that pressing space bar (or one of many other keys) will dismiss it. Please provide any additional information below. Attach a screenshot and backtrace if possible. I recommend *both* of these fixes: - alert() windows should always appear above extension popups. - Chrome should never perform a full-screen grab for any reason, because if anything else happens at the same time which causes Chrome to stop processing input, the X server may be rendered inoperable. In the specific case of extension popup bubbles, Chrome should either let the bubble stay where it is when the user clicks on another window, or it should close the bubble when the focus leaves.', '']

['Issue 107336: Show error bubble for Unrecoverable/Offline_unusable errors', 'It makes sense in M18 to start showing a wrench bubble when the user gets into one of the two generic Unrecoverable or Offline_unusable error states. 

We should badge the wrench, show a bubble with an error message and button to fix the issue, and a longer error message in preferences suggesting you restart sync along with a Learn more link.

Wrench: "Oops. Something went wrong with Chrome Sync. Please sign in again" [Sign in]

Where [Sign in] should disconnect them from Sync and taken them directly to the sign in page in preferences.

The Sign in section of preferences should say something similar: "Oops. Something went wrong with Chrome Sync. Please disconnect from Sync and sign in again. Learn more"

Note that we should be very specific in the scenarios we do/don't want to show the user an error

We DO want to show the bubble if the user ends up in an UnrecoverableError/Offline_unusable state that wasn't due to model association. There's a good change that restarting sync will fix the problem.

We DONT want to show the bubble if the error occurs during model association and is a per-data type error, because it's likely a bug with the data type itself, and restarting is unlikely to fix the issue. We don't really have any actionable advice to give the user in this case, they'd either need to clear the data of that type (maybe), or wait for the bug to get fixed in an update. The other data types should be successfully syncing independently, so I'm not sure it's helpful to tell the user about the problem.', '']

['Issue 145847: Let webapp update new tab area with update info/notices', "Right now, on newtab page, we only display static webapp icons. 
However, it will be greatly help webapp owners to increase user engagement if we add a method to allow webapp to update the new tab page with update info or notices for a given app.

For example, we can allow gmails to show how many new mails arrived.  This will give webapp owners a place to grab user's attention to increase user interaction between the app and user. 

Right now, chrome extension already allow extension to update the icon on status bar, which is used by many extension and seems to be effective. Adding this function to new tab page will be very welcome too.", '']

['Issue 279546: cbuildbot does not clean buildbot_archive directories from prior builds', "See
https://code.google.com/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=273779

If a machine is re-purposed 5 times to do a different build, it will keep creating new buildbot_archive board directories in /b/cbuild/shared_internal/buildbot_archive that never get cleaned up. Each eats about 40GB, so 5 boards ate 200GB.

Suggested fix is to delete all boards not related to the active board for the current build

Then, within a board directory, you have something like this:
buildbot_archive/x86-zgb_he-release/:
LATEST-release-R26-3701.B  R26-3701.81.0  R26-3701.82.0  R26-3701.83.0

We're currently keeping 3, and we could only keep the last one.", '']

['Issue 316552: Chrome freezes / crashes when uploading files - freezes on Windows application folder', "We're troubleshooting a persisting stability/crash issue one user is experiencing. 

The application folder/menu will freeze and Chrome will be completely unresponsive, essentially resulting in a crash/hard restart to recover.

- Downloads are fine, only uploads crash
- Tried new Chrome profile
- Tried Incognito
- Tried Canary
- Tried Safe mode
- Tried new Windows user
- Only happening in Chrome, no other browser
- No crash IDs
- No conflicts detected", '']

['Issue 338505: Extensions using chrome_settings_overrides manifest permission are disabled at every start', 'Version: 33.0.1750.46 beta
OS: Linux

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Install an extension from the CWS that sets manifest key chrome_settings_overrides.bookmarks_ui.hide_bookmarks_button to true. Accept the permissions dialog.
2. Exit and restart Chrome.
3. Go to chrome://extensions and observe the extension is incorrectly disabled. Enable the extension, and observe a permissions dialog asking to confirm re-enable because "it requires more permissions".

What is the expected output? What do you see instead?
Once the user is prompted for permissions at install time, Chrome should not re-prompt for additional permissions unless additional permissions are actually requested by the extension.

Please use labels and text to provide additional information.
Investigation shows that the permission state is being incorrectly serialized into a format that is not recognized at deserialization time. This appears to be due to a period character in the manifest permissions ID, which is unintentionally generating a nested dictionary at serialization time.', '']

['Issue 647185: Remove WebrtcAudioPrivate(Set/Get)ActiveSinkFunction', 'Output device selection functionality provided by WebrtcAudioPrivate(Set/Get)ActiveSinkFunction is covered by setSinkId, and the clients should switch to it.

Implementation of those (Set/Get)ActiveSinkFunction has the following problems:
1) What it does is that it iterates all controllers in the process and changes the device, regardless of discrepancies in sample rates or buffer sizes.
2) It introduces shared ownership of AudioOutputController objects we want to avoid.
3) Here (https://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/chrome/browser/extensions/api/webrtc_audio_private/webrtc_audio_private_api.cc?sq=package:chromium&dr=CSs&l=338)
it stores shared references to all the output controllers. But output controllers point to SyncReaders which they do not own
(https://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/media/audio/audio_output_controller.cc?cl=GROK&gsn=Create&rcl=1473909537&l=23) and which are owned by AudioEntries (https://cs.chromium.org/chromium/src/content/browser/renderer_host/media/audio_renderer_host.cc?cl=GROK&gsn=Create&rcl=1473909537&l=203).
So, webrtc private api may end up holding a reference to a partially corrupted controller (i.e. the one which points to a deleted sync reader - which does not manifest itself, because webrtc private api does not access sync reader).', '']

['Issue 89725: Make SpdySessions more resilient to connections dying', "Note that SpdySessions can go idle for a long time, during which the connection may quietly die and result in future packets getting blackholed by a NAT router or other intermediary.

Use SPDY PINGs to check for connection connectivity (and also keep it alive). This should be configurable since there are times when we wouldn't want to do this or we'd want to reduce the frequency (think mobile).

If the SpdySession dies, we need to establish a new one and retry URLRequests on that one.", '']

['Issue 478177: Clarification needed: how to save passwords on site with invalid SSL certificate', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.3; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.118 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. go to site with invalid certificate 
2. chrome won't ask and won't give option for saving password
3. compare to Firefox/IE where there are methods for making this work.

What is the expected behavior?
Allow in settings of chrome to input url of website with invalid SSL certificate, so that passwords will save.  (or some-such solution... anything really is better than nothing).  If Firefox/IE can build a solution, why can't Chrome?

What went wrong?
Several bug reports have been opened on this general topic, however none have answered the question, and since they are all either closed without legitimate explanation, or restricted to user input with no updates in 6+ months, I am forced to open a new bug.  Here is the history:
Issue 392789: "closed as "wont fix", despite a Lot of demand for a fix, including from chrome devs.
Issue 412827: open, but no one other than a dev is allowed to comment.  Issue explains the lack of documentation on how to save a password/save a certificate, along with many comments complaining about a lack of fix. Even Chrome devs commented that something is needed, but no updates have been made in >6 months, hence this re-opening of the issue.

Did this work before? No 

Chrome version: 41.0.2272.118  Channel: n/a
OS Version: 6.3
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 17.0 r0

As Many people have commented, there are (hundreds of?) thousands of valid sites used for internal portals (accessing dbs, cms's) which use secure SSL certificates that are not signed.  For all these users, as many have commented, Firefox is the only practical option.  The fact the main issue #392789 has been closed with "wont fix" means the developers of Chrome so far will not a) provide documentation on how to import a certificate to make saving passwords work, nor b) provide a method for all these valid, but unsigned certificates to be recognized by user input.  A straight-up rejection that there is a problem, or solution required does not respect the many users encountering it.

The primary concern with fixing this issue is that users will mistakenly accept a certificate, add their password unwittingly.  This is a true concern, and so passwords shouldn't be saved by default, there is no argument there.
What should happen is that somewhere, somehow, when a person very deliberately knows that their website with unsigned certificate is valid, they should be allowed to save said password. Without this, Chrome is shutting developers out from using the browser.

Final note. to quote a comment from September 2014 by a Chrome Dev (f...@chromium) in #412827
"We recognize that this is a problem for admins & developers and have been discussing ways to fix this. It isn't an easy problem: we need to balance 'average' user needs against this very corner-case scenario of a network admin or developer who visits large numbers of sites with passwords on self-signed certs.
Threatening to switch to Firefox is not productive. Please keep the conversation constructive."

6 months later, I really don't want to switch to Firefox, but the reality is it's the only option, as Chrome appears to have stopped work on the issue.  Again, this is not a "very corner-case" situation, but one met by thousands of users a day when they try to access legitimate, yet unsigned SSL sites.', '']

['Issue 298633: Make easier to debug the recovery workflow', "Collect and inspect the data on the current recovery environment is difficult because there's no interactive shell. Only the logs are recorded and can be inspected later, but every time a new value or file needs to be dumped at a certain point on the logs, the whole recovery workflow needs to be followed:
1. make the modification to the appropriate .sh file to dump the file.
2. run ./mod_image_for_recovery.sh (takes some time)
3. copy the image to an USB key: ./image_to_usb.sh -i recovery_image.bin (takes time)
4. put the usb key again on the DUT, reboot on the recovery image, wait until the recovery reaches the desired point again.
5. Inspect the logs.

This is extremely slow. An interactive shell makes the developer life easier.
Also, some documentation should be included on how to debug this recovery workflow should be included.", '']

['Issue 437140: Asynchronous popup are blocked by the popup blocker', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.3; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/39.0.2171.62 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Adds a click handler which makes an XHR request
2. At the completion of the request, open a popup

What is the expected behavior?
The popup should not be blocked.

What went wrong?
The popup has been blocked.

Did this work before? No 

Chrome version: 39.0.2171.62  Channel: n/a
OS Version: 6.3
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 15.0 r0

Two options:

1/ Chrome could implement something like reservePopup or something as such

2/ Chrome could use the new Promise object to detect if the promise has been created in an user event handler. I think that it could be possible to be quite smart with this.

The current common hack is to open a window anyway, and do something with it when the callback returns. It's bad UI imo, and not always applicable (for example, I want to open the Twitter share popup; on Android, it would ask me if I want to open it in the native application instead).", '']

["Issue 602994: EventSource 'onopen' event is inconsistent in state", 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; CrOS x86_64 7834.70.0) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/49.0.2623.112 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. create many s=EventSource(); s.onopen=function(){s.close()};

Either no connection is opened in this case and aborted, or all connections are opened and then closed

Some of the connections are closed before they are opened, and some are behaving as expected - the request is first seen at the server side, then onopen fires and the connection get closed.

Chrome version: 49.0.2623.112  Channel: stable
OS Version: 7834.70.0
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 21.0 r0

in Firefox, the connection is first seen on server, then onopen() is fired

This may happen only on slow hardware though', '']

['Issue 630734: Extension warning bubbles show option to remove extension even if unable to', 'What steps will reproduce the problem?
(1) Add a policy-controlled, force-installed extension that overrides proxy, ntp, search settings, home page, etc
(2) Observe warning bubble


What is the expected output?
The bubble should appear (fake policy extensions are an avenue for uws, so we want to be transparent), but should indicate that the extension is force-installed and cannot be removed.

What do you see instead?
The bubble offers to "restore settings", which would normally disable the extension.  Since the extension can't be disabled, this is meaningless.  
Assigning to catmullings@ who was looking for a good first UI bug.', '']

['Issue 203062: Automate Enterprise Enrollment: Successful Enrollment', 'The test itself is very simple to run manually, but can be difficult to get the machine properly prepared. Here's a high-level outline of the test:

1) "crosqa3.com" is pre-defined test domain enabled for Chrome OS Management.
2) Ensure that the device is ready for enrollment. I.e., TPM is not locked, and no user, tpm, policy, whitelist, or token data stored on SSD.
3a) Enroll device to domain crosqa3.com, with a valid user name and password for an existing, active user account.
3b) Device should indicate successful enrollment.
4) Clicking Done should land user on the Sign In screen.', '']

['Issue 388732: "Make a copy" is misleading. Save menus need to be revised.', "What steps will reproduce the problem?

   and Make a copy. This gives the impression the user cannot save 
   the document locally.
5) Make a copy doesn't make a copy to drive, it brings up a save locally dialog, which is completely confusing.

Improved UX:
A user should see File --> Save As

and upon clicking be given several options, including: google docs, local copy.

Make a copy should make a drive copy, not save locally.



Please use labels and text to provide additional information.", '']

["Issue 625794: Regression: Cursor is not seen at 'First name' field of sign in overlay on second instance via tap/touch.", "Chrome Version: 53.0.2785.6 (Official Build) dc1090fa0edd6091d6d99381c7ec40115c60327d-refs/branch-heads/2785@{#15}-32/64 bit
OS: Windows 10(Touch device)

Steps:
1. Launch Chrome, click on avtar icon and then click on Sign in to chrome button.
2. Select 'Create new account' from 'More option' menu via tap/touch, then tap on back button of sign in overlay.
3. Now again select 'Create new account' from 'More option' menu via tap/touch and observe.

Actual: Cursor is not seen at 'First name' field on second instance after tap/touch on 'Create new account'.

Expected: Cursor should be seen at 'First name' field on second instance after tap/touch on 'Create new account'.

This is a regression issue broken in M-51, below is bisect info.

Bad build: 51.0.2672.0

Narrow bisect:

['Issue 320316: Decreasing Javascript performance in web application that heavily makes use of JS (Chrome version 12 compared to 31)', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/31.0.1650.57 Safari/537.36

Hello Chromium team,

I have no bug report to submit but a performance issue:
I'm a developer of Openbravo (an open source web-based ERP system) and I recognize a hugh performance loss between older Chrome versions (~ 12) and current ones (~31). Openbravo makes heavily use of JavaScript and our customers report more and more a slower UI handling over the past months. And that although you the Google Chrome state with every new version that the JavaScript engine became faster...

So I did some performance tests on my computer with the official Openbravo demo system available online (so that you have the chance to retrace my test results):

And I stopped the time it took till the items in tab 'Lines' appeared. Then I closed the tab again and re-started the test. Here are my result:

Chrome Version 31.0.1650.57 m (Windows 7 Home Premium) - in seconds:
Test 1: 10,5
Test 2: 7,2
Test 3: 7,2
Test 4: 7,0
Test 5: 6,9
Test 6: 6,9
Test 7: 6,9

Test 6: 3,5

Thanks for your feedback! Please feel free to contact me in case of questions.

Victor Roeder

What is the expected behavior?
Chrome/Chromium should become faster with every version (as announced) and not slower.

What went wrong?
Performance decreased by ~50% from Chrome version 12 to 31.

Since I'm a software developer as well, please refrain from providing me tips that I should deactivate plugins or clear my browser cache... Thanks :-).

['Issue 79491: resources not specifying any caching behavior are only cached on the 2nd access', 'Chrome Version       : 10.0.648.204
OS Version: 6.1 (Windows 7, Windows Server 2008 R2)
URLs (if applicable) :
Other browsers tested:
Add OK or FAIL after other browsers where you have tested this issue:
  Firefox 4.x: OK
     IE 9: OK

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. clear all caches
2. go to some URL with links
3. click on a link
4. click 'back', the page is reloaded from network
5. click on another link
6. click 'back', now the page is reloaded from the memory cache

What is the expected result?
The page should be reloaded from the memory cache on the first try.

What happens instead?
Resources are only cached on the 2nd access. I believe this was intentional to avoid caching too much but the following scenario happens a lot:

- *click*
- "oops, not the link I wanted, let's go back"

And as a punishment, you get to reload the whole page from the network when pressing back :)

Maybe caching *to disk* can be done at the 2nd access, but caching to memory should always be done. It gives a much smoother browsing experience.

UserAgentString: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US) AppleWebKit/534.16 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/10.0.648.204 Safari/534.16,gzip(gfe)', '']

['Issue 269287: Enable sharing GpuMemoryBuffers across threads', "Currently it's possible that a GpuMemoryBuffer may be freed before we construct a GLImage from it. GLImage is being created asynchronously here:
https://code.google.com/p/chromium/codesearch#chromium/src/gpu/command_buffer/service/in_process_command_buffer.cc&q=in_process_&sq=package:chromium&l=490

While this command is enqueued the impl thread may free the GpuMemoryBuffer and as such invalidating the native buffer handle. When this occurs EGLImage creating fails with error 12300. 

When we pass the native handle to the GPU thread we also need to pass a reference to the underlying buffer to ensure the buffer isn't freed while we use its native buffer in the GPU thread.", '']

['Issue 705056: [Component Request] UI>Browser>Omnibox>ZeroSuggest', "1] Component Name: UI>Browser>Omnibox>ZeroSuggest

This term is relatively commonly used throughout the Chrome team, but it's not that widely used.  I know it somewhat violates Guideline 1, but I think the more description term UI>Browser>Omnibox>OnFocusSuggestions will be less discoverable by the people who need to file bugs against this component.  (In other words, it works better for Guideline 4.)

(The ZeroSuggest name came from the idea of offering suggestions with no prefix, i.e., zero prefix, instead of as-you-type suggestions which have a user typing something, i.e., a prefix for the suggestions.)

2] Parent Component (e.g. Blink, UI>Browser, etc...): UI>Browser>Omnibox

3] Description of Component: Suggestions displayed on omnibox focus (both contextual and non-contextual)

4] Admin/ Owner: mpearson

5] Please specify what triage practices will be followed for the component
(i.e. what team will do it and how frequently).

The omnibox team will do it.  Our current omnibox triage doc will have us triaging this component every other day (excluding weekends).", '']

['Issue 352635: The definition of "stable firmware" seems a little strange', 'For pit and pi, we had the following situation:

1. We had .90 firmware that was not marked as stable.

2. We got .93 firmware and marked that as stable.


That makes sense, but it had the side effect that if you had a device with .90 and then you put on a new image that bundled .93, we wouldn't update .90 to .93.

It seems like "stable" should be a list of known stable versions that we won't update, not a boolean flag.


See http://crosbug.com/p/26826', '']

['Issue 146451: ConstrainedWindow(new): Fix regressions on Mac', "The new Constrained Windows implementation on Mac has several regressions. These need to be fixed before it can be enabled by default.

Here's what I have so far. We'll want to add unit tests for most of these:
switch focus
  - quit should not quit and instead focus on sheet
  - close window should not close window and instead focus on sheet

keyboard
  - clicking on disabled area, sheet should maintain keyboard focus
  - escape and return dismiss sheet
  - switch to new tab, new tab gains keyboard focus
  - switch back to tab with sheet, sheet regains keyboard focus

disable
  - tab dragging disabled for tabs with sheets
  - switching to fullscreen disabled for tabs with sheets

navigation
  - menu commands such as Open New Tab Page, Clear Browsing Data, etc.. are enabled and open UI in a new tab
  - reload, back and forward are enabled and correctly close the sheet

sheet placement
  - showing and hiding infobar while sheet is open works.
  - sheet is positioned N pixels below the omnibox even when infobar is showing

["Issue 133218: [extension] Only checking 'unprivileged' key is not enough when loading extension api schema", "In ExtensionAPI defined in chrome/common/extensions, when loading extension api schema, it only checks the existence of 'unprivileged' key in schema file to determine whether the extension API should be inserted into completely_unprivileged_apis_ list. It is not enough because the value of 'unprivileged' key MUST be 'true' for unprivileged extension API.\n\nSo besides checking the existence of 'unprivileged' key, we also must check the value to ensure the correct semantic of 'unprivileged' key.", '']

['Issue 126513: Use paint coverage information to skip sampling/drawing unfilled portions of sparse layers', 'Suppose we paint a layer that itself is mostly sparse. E.g. a layer that is 256x256 but empty except for two partially transparent rectangles at:
  Rect(0,0,100,10)
  Rect(0,100,100,10)

Right now, when we draw that layer, we DrawQuad a full 256x256 quad, and sample from the entire 256x256 sample. When the layer is a non-root layer, there may be a performance win by avoiding sampling/drawing in the unfilled parts of the quads in the first place.

To do this, suppose we maintain an SkRegion representing where a layer has content versus where it is empty.

When we go to draw a tile for that layer, instead of issuing a giant quad, we would instead generate a vertex buffer for the layer that has rectangles only for where the layer is opaque. So, in the case above, when we draw the layer, we would do 1 draw call with a 2-quad vertex buffer.', '']

['Issue 476428: Move DOM attributes to prototype chains.', 'Change description:
Blink has placed DOM attributes on instances instead of prototypes. However, the Web IDL spec requires that DOM attributes must be placed on prototype chains (except for a few exceptions such as static attributes and [Unforgeable].) We move DOM attributes on instances to prototype chains following the spec.

Changes to API surface:
Typical issues that web developers would face to are as follows, but not limited to.
- JSON.stringify(domObject)
  returns {}, which was {domAttr1: value1, domAttr2, value2, ...}
- "use strict"; domObject.readonlyAttr = anyValue
  throws an exception.  Before, just ignored.
- domObject.hasOwnProperty("feature1")
  returns false even if feature1 is supported.
  ("feature1" in domObject) is the correct way.

Links:
Public standards discussion:
https://heycam.github.io/webidl/#es-attributes

Support in other browsers:
Internet Explorer: supported
Firefox: supported
Safari: not supported', '']

['Issue 276579: Add a ScheduledActionAbortDraw to help flush our pipeline', 'Adding this action will allow us to flush the pending/active tree pipeline in corner cases without crazy branching in the Scheduler.', '']

['Issue 154853: Too many flushes when uploading textures', 'There is almost a flush between each texture upload, even though it should only be 1 per 4 uploads.

The cause is attempting to get the value of pending queries which implicitly inserts flushes.

A potential fix would be to remove the call to processPqueries in ThrottledTextureUploader::beginQuery.', '']

['Issue 169025: Webstore icon in the launcher should be special-cased', 'two concerns with the webstore icon in the app launcher:

1) Currently the webstore icon shows with the tab treatment we use for all hosted apps, but I think we should special-case the icon.  Simplest approach is to give it the v2 app icon treatment even though it launches in a browser tab.  Jeff, thoughts?

2) By default, the text is gettting truncated to "Chrome We..." which is not great.  We need to some some solution such that the text appears without getting cut.  Perhaps we need to change the label to "web store" and let the chrome logo in the icon speak for itself?', '']

['Issue 476747: chromeos-install output cleanup', 'chromeos-install gives a lot of (unnecessary?) output, including in some cases some messages that look like errors but are perfectly normal.

For example, installing gizmo 6971.0.0 to a panther prints this message:

  Cannot tell where /sys/dev/char/8:3/subsystem links to: No such file or directory.

Which sounds like an error, but is a normal condition for a non-UBI volume.


Note: this may be a subset of overall chromeos-install cleanup/rewrite at http://crbug.com/269119.', '']

['Issue 652260: Enable system health metrics smoke test in system health benchmark smoke test suite', 'Currently, our system health benchmark smoke test only assert that all system health stories run without having errors, e.g: crashes.\n\nHowever, it might be possible to enable all the tracing categories required for all the system health metrics (memory, loading, cpuMetric...) & assert that the most important metrics do exist & are non zeroes in the result. This would help prevent issue 649061.', '']

["Issue 150601: Can't resize a textarea with touch", "Google Chrome 23.0.1266.0 (Official Build 156729) canary
Platform 2901.0.0 (Official Build) canary-channel link
WebKit 537.10 (@128486)

What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Go to a page with a textarea (eg. http://www.w3schools.com/tags/showit.asp?filename=tryhtml_textarea)
2. When running with --enable-touch-events, touch and drag on the resize handle

What is the expected output? What do you see instead?
We should probably resize the text area using touch in this case.  However, I'm not sure we have a good way of doing this today without adding touch event handlers and so preventing impl-thread scrolling on the page.

Rob, what do you think the right solution is here?  Whatever it is, we should probably use it for <input type=range> too (which relies on touch handlers today).  Textareas are probably way more common than range input.", '']

['Issue 225029: Require user gesture for window.open', 'Currently we allow window.open in a background page for v2 apps without requiring any user gesture. This leads to apps that when launched just navigate to a URL. (just like any v1 bookmark app)\n\nWe could prevent this behavior by requiring a user gesture (like clicking a button or a link) on the app before invoking window.open - if not, we can reject the call.', '']

["Issue 392303: Every builder should describe the trybot it's equivalent to.", "I filed issue 391513 about failures on http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.memory.fyi/builders/Chromium%20Mac%20%28valgrind%29%282%29/ and http://build.chromium.org/p/chromium.memory.fyi/builders/Windows%20Unit%20%28DrMemory%20full%29%20%283%29/, and the person I assigned it to was confused about how to run enough tryjobs to check that their fix works.

If these bots' landing pages included something like:

 1) Schedule an equivalent tryjob with `git cl try -m tryserver.chromium -b win_drmemory`
 2) Schedule a tryjob for the failing tests with `git cl try -m tryserver.chromium -b win_drmemory:content_unittests,browser_tests`
 3) There is no trybot that runs the failing tests in this configuration.

it would waste less time for people trying to debug their code.", '']
