['Issue 532296: DevTools: Network throttling behavior is confusing', 'UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_9_5) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/45.0.2454.85 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Open up device mode in devtools
2. Turn on throttling
3. Close device mode

OR

1. Turn on throttling in devtools
2. Close devtools

What is the expected behavior?
Throttling should no longer be enabled in the current tab or in other tabs.

What went wrong?
Throttling stays enabled as you browse in any tab where you have devtools open.

Did this work before? Yes Chrome 44

Chrome version: 45.0.2454.85  Channel: n/a
OS Version: OS X 10.9.5
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 18.0 r0

This has actually confused me a number of times, and I have seen other coworkers run into it too. I believe the behavior here changed in Chrome 45.

What I find confusing is that the throttling controls apply to the Network panel, but also show up under the device settings. (I noticed issue #504882, but I think that is also the wrong approach. Auto enabling throttling when testing a responsive design would cause even more confusion.)

I think the way it used to work was that when you closed the device panel the throttling would also be disabled, but now it seems to persist.

I also noticed #504027 which I believe landed as well, but unfortunately I didn't make the connection that the exclamation point in the network tab meant that my connection was throttled. I actually thought it was Chrome alerting me that it was seeing really awful download speeds, and there was something WRONG with my internet connection. I spent about 10 minutes debugging, and even contacted our CDN thinking it was an issue on their end until I hovered over the network tab :(

I have a few ideas that I think will make this a lot less confusing

1. Remove the throttling settings completely from the device settings. I just now noticed they also live in the network tab, and they make a lot more sense there.

2. If the throttling is going to stay in the device settings then it should be independent from the one in the network settings. Some people will turn on device mode to test things out then turn it off without ever going to the network tab or realizing that the setting is inherited.

3. Do not make throttle settings sticky. For me personally, I think if the throttling settings only persisted for the current tab it would be easier to understand. I often want to test throttling for a specific page. It is very unlikely that I want it to apply to every page I visit. If I open devtools in a new tab I do not expect that tab to also be throttled.

4. Replace the exclamation point icon in the network tab with a different icon or a badge with the word "Throttled". Perhaps there is a better design treatment, but the exclamation point to me illustrates that there is a problem with my network connection and not that I have enabled throttling in Chrome.', '']

['Issue 249848: Infinite loop in SSLClientSocketNSS::Core::OnSendComplete', 'Version: 29.0.1535.3
OS: Windows 7 x64.

What steps will reproduce the problem?
Not exactly sure. Looks like the steps are
1. Open https site.
2. Switch off internet in the middle of site loading/go in and out of sleep mode.

What is the expected output?
A page with network error.

What do you see instead?
Browser hangs with browser process occupying 100% of one cpu core.

I attached debugger to the browser process and I see an infinite loop in
SSLClientSocketNSS:Core::OnSendComplete function.

The loop starts at 2257 line of ssl_client_socket_nss.cc

The check on user_read_buf is satisfied and DoPayloadRead is called.
In this function pending_read_result_ equals to kNoPendingReadResult. So the execution skips large if up to PR_Read function. PR_Read returns -1. Then local variable amount_in_read_buffer is filled with zero which is result of function memio_GetReadableBufferSize. Then check total_bytes_read == user_read_buf_len_ fails since total_bytes_read is zero. Finally, error handling starts. The first if is skipped since total_bytes_read is zero. The second if is skipped since client_auth_cert_needed_ equals false. The third if is executed since rv is -1. PR_GetError() returns -5998. This error is recognized as PR_WOULD_BLOCK_ERROR and is transformed by MapNSSClientError/MapNSSError to -1. So execution skips the rest of the function and DoPayloadRead returns with -1.

Then check on user_write_buf is not satisifed and rv_write remains equal to ERR_IO_PENDING (which is -1).

Finally, DoTranportIO is called. nss_bufs_ is not NULL, so BufferSend is called. First, it checks that transport_send_busy_ equals to false. Then memio_GetWriteParams is called. It returns len1 equal to 0x17de and len2 equal to 0x2727. len equals to 0x3f05. The functions initializes IOBuffer and copies data to it. OnNetworkTaskRunner returns true so DoBufferSend is called. In DoBufferSend function, detached_ equals to false. Then TCPClientSocketWin::Write function is called. This function calls WSASend and gets -1 as a result. WSAGetLastError returns 0x2746=10054=WSAECONNRESET. MapSystemError maps it to ERR_CONNECTION_RESET which is returned by TCPClientSocketWin::Write. OnNSSTaskRunner returns true, so the next if in DoBufferSend is skipped and it returns ERR_CONNECTION_RESET too. BufferSend sets error code to nss_bufs_ and returns ERR_CONNECTION_RESET as well. DoTransportIO sets network_moved to true and so returns true (transport_recv_eof_ is false and BufferRecv returns ERR_IO_PENDING).

Finally, while condition evaluates to true and cycle continues all other again.', '']

['Issue 436445: [CSS Grid Layout] Wrong space passed to computeNormalizedFractionBreadth', "Our track sizing algorithm is still based on the initial pseudocode written by MS engineers[1].

In order to compute the sizes of flex tracks, it uses a function called computeNormalizedFlexBreadths which can receive as an argument either one of the following:
a) AvailableSpace 
b) max-content of item crossing the track

The latter is correctly implemented, but in the case of the former, we're passing the FreeSpace instead of the AvailableSpace. This causes weird issues sizing flex tracks.

[1] http://www.w3.org/TR/2013/WD-css3-grid-layout-20130402/", '']

['Issue 236673: Password filling failing for nytimes.com', 'Currently on nytimes.com, when you save your password after logging in, the password will not be available to fill later (assuming you navigated to the login form from the main page). This is because the homepage has a hidden form that has the same markup for username, password, and action as the actual login form and we don't clear pending_login_managers_ on every navigation so when we save the password we considered it bound to "http://www.nytimes.com" not "https://myaccount.nytimes.com". There are at least two possible fixes.

1) Clear out pending_login_managers_ on every main frame navigation.
2) Require signon_realm to match for forms to be considered matched.

2) is probably not necessary if 1) is done, but I'm not sure why we don't have this check in place regardless.', '']

['Issue 509380: DevTools: Device Mode - Larger viewport without fit should be scrollable', "Steps to Reproduce:

3. Turn off the viewport fit option.

5. Try to see the parts of the page that don't fit in the viewport.

Current behavior:

Impossible to get around the rest of the viewport. You can scroll up and down, but that is it. Nothing to the right can be gotten to.

Expected behavior:

There be some way to facilitate seeing the rest of the viewport, say special scrollbars to indicate they aren't a part of page content but Device Mode.

Use-case:

Trying to debug some reports of wonkyness in Chrome [1] for Material Design Lite. Fitting the viewport makes the issues so small and blurry that you can't accurately recreate the view to cause the problem. ['Issue 633460: TranslateHelper needs to filter some parameters in a translate request from browser side', 'Currently when TranslateHelper(renderer side) got a translate request from browser side, it uses the parameters directly to concatenate out a JS string to execute. 
'
std::string script = "cr.googleTranslate.translate('" + source_lang_ + "','" + target_lang_ + "')";
'

Although this is invoked in response to a browser message, and the message flows in a less secure direction, we might want to protect ourselves if source_lang contains unexpected punctuation, in case souce_lang is somehow taken by the browser from some user or page input.

We need to add some guard mechanism here. 
WDYT? Thanks.', '']

['Issue 330430: Chrome ignores x-webkit-deflate-frame rejection from servers.', "UserAgent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/31.0.1650.63 Safari/537.36

Steps to reproduce the problem:
1. Connect to a websocket server that doesn't support the x-webkit-deflate-frame extension.
2. See that the server follows protocol implementation and rejects extension by NOT sending back the x-webkit-deflate-frame extension.
3. Chrome still deflates frames.

What is the expected behavior?
Chrome shouldn't deflate frames when the server didn't acknowledge the extension using the header Sec-WebSocket-Extensions: x-webkit-deflate-frame

What went wrong?
Chrome isn't following the websocket extension protocol and doesn't check the extensions supported by the server, as described in http://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-tyoshino-hybi-websocket-perframe-deflate-04#section-3

Did this work before? N/A 

Chrome version: 31.0.1650.63  Channel: stable
OS Version: 6.1 (Windows 7, Windows Server 2008 R2)
Flash Version: Shockwave Flash 11.9 r900

Here is a wireshark example:

GET /test HTTP/1.1
Upgrade: websocket
Connection: Upgrade
Host: localhost:8080
Origin: http://localhost:8080
Pragma: no-cache
Cache-Control: no-cache
Sec-WebSocket-Key: tkKgfFfkiWTH0TQWrzrPPQ==
Sec-WebSocket-Version: 13
Sec-WebSocket-Extensions: x-webkit-deflate-frame
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/31.0.1650.63 Safari/537.36

HTTP/1.1 101 Switching Protocols
Upgrade: WebSocket
Connection: Upgrade
Sec-WebSocket-Accept: YP+y/QPdWcv4VWy7gRFSsbAqlzc=
Sec-WebSocket-Version: 13

And then, Chrome proceeds to send compressed data nonetheless.", '']

['Issue 282672: DelayBasedTimeSource::NextTickTarget not robust to overflow', 'After r220462 (https://chromiumcodereview.appspot.com/23593003), LayerTreeHostAnimationTestNoBackgroundTickingWithoutActiveTree.RunSingleThread_DirectRenderer crashes for me on Linux.  This does not appear to be happening on the waterfall.

[20150:20150:0830/154330:8635916565269:FATAL:delay_based_time_source.cc(221)] Check failed: now <= new_tick_target. now = 8635916565196; new_tick_target = -8543952616000; new_interval = 4000; tick_target = 0; intervals_elapsed = -2135988154

["Issue 644892: [Predator] run.sh can't handle symlinked directories", 'When trying to run the unit tests for Findit from a symlinked directory, Python crashes with a very unhelpful error message. We should catch the OSError and either give a useful/legible/actionable error message or else just do the right thing to avoid the OSError in the first place.


$> ls -l findit-crash
lrwxrwxrwx 1 wrengr eng 36 Sep  1 08:20 findit-crash -> chromium-srcs/infra/appengine/findit
$> cd findit-crash
$> ./util_scripts/run.sh test
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/local/google/home/wrengr/findit-crash/util_scripts/../../../test.py", line 127, in <module>
    [python_bin, os.path.join('bootstrap', 'remove_orphaned_pycs.py')])
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py", line 535, in check_call
    retcode = call(*popenargs, **kwargs)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py", line 522, in call
    return Popen(*popenargs, **kwargs).wait()
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py", line 710, in __init__
    errread, errwrite)
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/subprocess.py", line 1327, in _execute_child
    raise child_exception
OSError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory', '']

['Issue 686221: Add shared_bitmap to cc.mojom.TextureMailbox', "Right now cc.mojom.TextureMailbox does not have a shared_bitmap like cc::TextureMailbox, which is not problematic at this moment because cc.mojom.TexutreMailbox is currently only used for copy requests and copy requests don't need the shared_bitmap field. However, we should be able to add it to the mojom struct without much trouble.", '']

['Issue 457667: Include a more comprehensive test-suite for ContentBrowserClient::OpenURL on all platforms', 'We currently have a single test for ContentBrowserClient::OpenURL in the ChromeContentBrowserClientTest unit-test suite, which can only be ran on synchronous implementations.\n\nWhile we should avoid end up testing chrome::Navigate again, it would be good to have a number of tests covering not just Desktop, but also Android where this method can be asynchronous. The difference between opening a new tab or re-using an existing tab, as well as Incognito mode, would be good to cover in these tests.', '']

["Issue 287785: Can't commit new file on Windows - presubmit script fails on license check.", "1. Create CL which adds new file with \r\n line endings and correct license.
2. Execute svn pset svn:eol-style LF for this file.
3. Execute gcl commit or gcl presubmit command for the CL.

Presubmit checks says that license doesn't match.

CheckLicense function in presubmit_canned_checks.py reads all files in the CL in 'rb' mode. In this mode \r\n are not replaced by \n and hence the file doesn't match the license regular expression. Replacing 'rb' mode to 'r' or converting file to unix line ending makes presubmit check pass.", '']

['Issue 87320: Export net-log dumps as JSON rather than text', "Currently when users provide us with NetLogs for analysis, they give us pretty-printed text dumps.

My proposal is to remove this pretty-printed text format, and instead have users export a less human-readable JSON format.

The benefit to using a JSON file format over text, is it can easily be imported into the net-internals frontend. This would allow bug investigators to load the dump file into Chrome, and more quickly analyze and filter the dump using the tools we have built into the about:net-internals frontend. I expect to add more stuff to correlate performance and asynchronous events into net-internals which will make this ability even more compelling. Imagine just loading up a net-internals log and seeing immediately the cause of the slowness rather than manually stitching together the events!

There are of course some tradeoffs in doing this, but I am convinced it is worthwhile:

-----
Pros:
-----

  - Quicker diagnosis given netlog dumps.

  - The same tools we build into net-internals for analyzing dumps would be beneficial to all users, which reduces the need to send us dumps in the first place.

  - Not being constrained by text-base visualizations, we can make richer presentations of the log info using HTML. For instance, can display information in mouseovers, jump to dependencies using hyperlinks, etc. (We can technically do this today, but it is quite annoying having to maintain duplicate presentation layers).

  - Symmetry between export/import of data. (Right now the export and import are not reversible, and in fact we have a different export format being used by the command-line-flag logging mode).

-----
Downsides:
-----

  - Harder for users to manually redact information.

Counter argument:
Search-and-replace should still work as effectively as it did before. Most users don't end up redacting the information anyway, and when they do, it tends to cause problems in understanding what happened anyway.

  - File format version will change over time, making it impossible to load old logs using new versions of Chrome (and vice versa).

Counter argument:
Yes, this sucks. However in practice I expect the file format to be fairly stable, so recentish dumps will load in recentish builds of chrome. Mainly we are dealing with recentish dumps anyway (since we almost always ask users to reproduce in the latest build of Chrome), so I don't think this will be a big nuisance. When it does become an issue, the solution would be to download an older build of Chromium off the buildbot and use that to load it up (I don't want to guarantee backwards compatibility between Chrome versions).", '']

['Issue 145118: If-then-else support in GRIT', 'Grit now supports nested ifs but it doesn't support if-else, so you have to write

  <if cond="pp_defined('foo')">
    ...
  </if>
  <if cond="not pp_defined('foo')">
    ...
  </if>

In my experience this is difficult to read, and saintlou agrees. It would be nice if we could write

  <if cond="pp_defined('foo')">
    ...
  <else/>
    ...
  </if>

This would require some minor rejiggering of Grit internals. Conditions are currently tested by iterating up the XML hierarchy looking for surrounding <if> elements. Instead we could do an earlier pass over the whole tree and drop unused elements. This would have to happen once per output language and context since those can be tested in <if> statements.', '']

['Issue 547949: ::first-letter visibility:visible in visibility:hidden parent interop difference in Chrome vs Edge/Firefox', 'See http://jsfiddle.net/boggydigital/L2bcev9s/2/ (original version: http://jsfiddle.net/L2bcev9s/ - simplified to remove unrelated styles).

Reported as Edge issue by external web developer, is not known to cause live site interop issues. Filing against Chrome since it's not consistent with Edge/Firefox for ::first-letter visibility specifically and not consistent with the spec (as I understand it).

Visibility is not specified to apply to first-letter (if my reading is correct) so shouldn't have effect on ::first-letter descendants of visibility:hidden elements. This looks to be true for ::first-line, but not ::first-letter in Chrome (even though both get computed value of "visible" - that looks correct by itself).

http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-selectors/#first-line
http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-selectors/#first-letter
http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css-pseudo-4/#first-line-styling
http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css-pseudo-4/#first-letter-styling', '']

['Issue 569683: OOPIF: Race condition is possible between commit and cancelling a pending navigation', 'It is currently possible to have a race between pending navigation and commit with the following sequence of events:

1. Browser process starts a cross-process navigation in a pending RenderFrameHost
2. The document commits in the RenderFrame sending a DidCommitProvisionalLoad IPC to the browser process.
*3. Prior to receiving the DidCommitProvisionalLoad IPC, the navigation is cancelled in the browser process. This results in the deletion of the pending RenderFrameHost.

In step 2, the RenderFrameProxy is deleted when the pending RenderFrame is committed. 
In step 3, since the pending RenderFrameHost is deleted, the browser process drops the DidCommitProvisionalLoad message and now the two processes are in mismatched state.

When a navigation in pending RenderFrameHost is cancelled, we need to send an message to the renderer process notifying it and attaching the necessary state to recreate the RenderFrameProxy if it was already deleted due to the race.', '']

['Issue 97489: The saveAsMHTML extension should clean-up the temporary file used to generate the MHTML.', "The experimental API to save a page as MHTML creates a temporary file that is not current deleted.

There is a way to make the BlobStorageController auto-delete the file when it's done using it (see webkit/blob/deletable_file_reference.h), however that requires creating a scoped_refptr<DeletableFileReference>, and we need a good context to hold that ptr.
The SavePageAsMHTMLFunction gets deleted immediately after the result is sent to the extension process, and is not a right place for that scoped_refptr to be (the file would most likely get deleted before the extension process has created a blob with it).
We would need to create a self-owned object that would hold that scoped_refptr and listen for an ACK from the extension process that the Blob has been created, at which point it would deleted itself (and released the scoped_refptr). It would auto-delete if the extension process crashes.", '']

We have two problems here:
